Certainly! To sort the elements of the periodic table based on their atomic numbers in C#, you can use the `System.Linq` namespace. I'll demonstrate how to achieve this, as well as how to create a scatterplot using the `OxyPlot` library, which is a popular plotting library for .NET applications.

First, let's sort the elements based on their atomic numbers:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Define elements with their atomic numbers
        var elements = new List<(string Name, int AtomicNumber)>
        {
            ("Chromium", 24),
            ("Neodymium", 60),
            ("Cadmium", 48),
            ("Hafnium", 72),
            ("Silver", 47),
            ("Thorium", 90),
            ("Sulfur", 16),
            ("Xenon", 54),
            ("Tin", 50),
            ("Carbon", 6)
        };

        // Sort elements by atomic number
        var sortedElements = elements.OrderBy(e => e.AtomicNumber).ToList();

        // Display sorted elements
        Console.WriteLine("Elements sorted by atomic number:");
        foreach (var element in sortedElements)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"{element.Name}: {element.AtomicNumber}");
        }
    }
}
```

Running this code will give you the following output:

```
Elements sorted by atomic number:
Carbon: 6
Sulfur: 16
Chromium: 24
Silver: 47
Cadmium: 48
Tin: 50
Xenon: 54
Neodymium: 60
Hafnium: 72
Thorium: 90
```

Next, let's create a scatterplot to visualize the relationship between atomic numbers and corresponding elements using the `OxyPlot` library. First, you need to install the `OxyPlot.Core` and `OxyPlot.WindowsForms` packages via NuGet.

Here's how you can create a scatterplot:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using OxyPlot;
using OxyPlot.Series;
using OxyPlot.WindowsForms;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Define elements with their atomic numbers
        var elements = new List<(string Name, int AtomicNumber)>
        {
            ("Chromium", 24),
            ("Neodymium", 60),
            ("Cadmium", 48),
            ("Hafnium", 72),
            ("Silver", 47),
            ("Thorium", 90),
            ("Sulfur", 16),
            ("Xenon", 54),
            ("Tin", 50),
            ("Carbon", 6)
        };

        // Sort elements by atomic number
        var sortedElements = elements.OrderBy(e => e.AtomicNumber).ToList();

        // Create a scatter plot
        var plotModel = new PlotModel { Title = "Atomic Number vs Elements" };
        var scatterSeries = new ScatterSeries { MarkerType = MarkerType.Circle };

        foreach (var element in sortedElements)
        {
            scatterSeries.Points.Add(new ScatterPoint(element.AtomicNumber, 0, 4, 0, element.Name));
        }

        plotModel.Series.Add(scatterSeries);

        // Create plot view
        var plotView = new PlotView
        {
            Model = plotModel,
            Dock = System.Windows.Forms.DockStyle.Fill
        };

        // Create a form and add the plot view
        var form = new System.Windows.Forms.Form
        {
            Text = "Scatterplot",
            ClientSize = new System.Drawing.Size(800, 600)
        };
        form.Controls.Add(plotView);

        // Show the form
        System.Windows.Forms.Application.Run(form);
    }
}
```

This code will display a scatterplot with atomic numbers on the x-axis and a placeholder on the y-axis (since we're primarily interested in atomic numbers). Each point represents an element, and you can hover over the points to see their names. 

Make sure to set up your project to use Windows Forms and include the necessary OxyPlot references before running this code.
